-- Southern China Rains, Flooding Leave 211 Dead, Displace 2.4 Million People
-- Bloomberg News
-- 2010-06-24T03:03:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/southern-china-rains-flooding-leave-211-dead-displace-2-4-million-people.html

          
          
             Flooding in southern China has
killed at least 211 people, left 119 missing and displaced 2.4
million as of 4 p.m. yesterday, the Ministry of Civil Affairs
said. More rainfall is forecast for today.  
 Direct economic losses are estimated at 43.3 billion yuan
($6.35 billion), including the collapse of 215,000 housing units
and complete destruction of crops on 277,800 hectares of land,
the ministry said in a  statement  posted on its website yesterday.  
 Jiangxi, Hunan, Fujian will receive more heavy rain today,
intensifying flooding, which has affected more than 30 million
people in 10 provinces, according to  China Meteorological
Administration .  
 Hunan will have the “widest and strongest” rain today,
Rednet, a news website based in the province,  said , citing the
Hunan Provincial Meteorological Bureau. A total of 8.3 million
people in Hunan are affected by flooding, the website reported.  
 Rainfall around Jiangxi province’s Fuhe river, whose banks
burst twice and forced almost 100,000 residents to be evacuated
this week, will be 60 to 80 millimeters today, according to
Jiangxi News, a local website.  
